Cleaning up environmental salinity data: Using rolling 30 day average to remove data points that are +/- 2 standard deviations away from mean.

Notes:
-Accessed and downloaded all data on September 30, 2020.

-I downloaded all data available from 1/1/2017-12/31/2019. None of the following data sources had air temperature so I’ll look into additional data sources for that.

-China camp http://cdmo.baruch.sc.edu/aqs/zips.cfm Data logged every 15 minutes. Requested citation format: NOAA National Estuarine Research Reserve System (NERRS). System-wide Monitoring Program. Data accessed from the NOAA NERRS Centralized Data Management Office website: http://cdmo.baruch.sc.edu/; accessed 30 September 2020.

-Richardson Bay/NERR data. Data logged every 15 minutes.Data from Matt Ferner and Anna Deck.

-EOS https://oceanview.pfeg.noaa.gov/erddap/tabledap/rtcctdRTCysi.html. This is the archived data. There is also data at https://oceanview.pfeg.noaa.gov/erddap/tabledap/rtcctdRTCysi.html but I did not use this. Data logged every 6 minutes. time in UTC.

-Point Fort http://erddap.cencoos.org/erddap/tabledap/fort-point.html?time%2Csea_water_temperature%2Csea_water_temperature_qc_agg%2Cz&time%3E%3D2020-09-20T21%3A07%3A41Z&time%3C%3D2020-09-29T12%3A00%3A00Z. time in UTC. Data logged every 6 minutes.

Make a custon function to calculate mean, sd, 95% confidence interval where x is a numeric vector. Here “hi” and “lo” are defined as 2 strandard deviations away from mean. This creates a functin so you don’t need to change anything here/this step does not manipulate the data. You can change the equation to define the hi and low as 3 or however many sds away you would like. na.rm=TRUE removes any “NA” values. “ret” are the new columns it’ll add when you run this on a df.

custom_stat_fun_2<-function(x, na.rm=TRUE){
  m<-mean(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  s<- sd(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  hi<-m+2*s
  lo<-m-2*s
  ret<-c(mean=m, stdev=s, hi.95=hi, lo.95=lo)
}

Roll apply using custom stat function. Monthly rolling average, weekly didn’t get rid of all outliers. Width will depend on the frequencey of the time series. Data collected every 6 minutes so width=1680 is 7 days, 3360 is 14 days, 7200 is 30 days. 240 observations per day. select = what paramter do you want to apply the rolling average to, in this case we’re interested in salinity. FUN= is the fuction we just created.

When I do 7 day and 14 day rolling average, a clear outlier remains. 30 days seems to be the best approach. In my origonal data dive of all the raw environmental data (https://cmwegener.github.io/thesis/bouy_data_dive.png) salinity at eos seemed to have the most extreme outliers. I want to remove outliers the same way for all my enviornmental data so I figured if this method works here, it should work for all the other ones.

s_data_rollstats<-eos%>%
  tq_mutate(
    select= salinity,
    mutate_fun= rollapply,
    width= 7200,
    align= "right",
    by.column= FALSE,
    FUN= custom_stat_fun_2,
    na.rm= TRUE)
## Warning in zoo(y, order.by = index(x), ...): some methods for "zoo" objects do
## not work if the index entries in 'order.by' are not unique

Look at the new df in the environment and sort hi and lo columns (or just graph it). Looks like it worked. Let’s filter and graph.

For filtering I’m selecting to keep values that are inbetween “hi.95” and “lo.95” that we calculted using our custom funtion.

NOTE: since I’m doing a 30 day rolling average, the first 30 days (or 7200 observations) will be “NA”.

clean_data<-filter(s_data_rollstats, salinity <hi.95 & salinity >lo.95)

eos_graph<- ggplot(data = clean_data, mapping = aes(x = date, y = salinity, color=salinity)) + geom_point()+
  labs(title="Salinity data from EOS resesarch pier",
       subtitle="01/01/2017 - 12/31/2019",
       caption= "data courtesy of CeNCOOS")

ggplot(data = clean_data, mapping = aes(x = date, y = salinity, color=salinity)) + geom_point()+
  labs(title="Salinity data from EOS resesarch pier",
       subtitle="01/01/2017 - 12/31/2019",
       caption= "data courtesy of CeNCOOS")

Looks like some outliers still remain. This data set has a “flag” column and it looks like they flagged most of the “0” salinity values. I’m going to remove those first and then contiue with the same method as above. Maybe this is the first step I should do to all my environmental data?

Remove salinity points where sea_water_practical_salinity_qc_tests = 4 which indicates FAIL.

From ERDDAP:
sea_water_practical_salinity_qc_agg { Int32 _ChunkSizes 2045, 1; Int32 _FillValue 2; String _Unsigned “true”; Int32 actual_range 1, 4; String flag_meanings “PASS NOT_EVALUATED SUSPECT FAIL MISSING”; Int32 flag_values 1, 2, 3, 4, 9; String ioos_category “Other”; String long_name “Salinity QARTOD Aggregate Quality Flag”; Int32 missing_value 2; String standard_name “aggregate_quality_flag”; }

fp<-filter(fp, sea_water_practical_salinity_qc_agg!=4)
